      <div class="stat-label">Net Cash</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model. For a capital-intensive midstream energy company like The Williams Companies, valuing future cash flows directly is vital due to large capital expenditures masking true long-term cash generation capabilities.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>WMB generated <strong>$1.005 billion</strong> in free cash flow in FY2025. This accounts for operating cash flows minus their substantial capital expenditures.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We grow FCF at <strong>4% per year</strong> for 5 years. This reflects WMB's stable fee-based pipeline revenue model, steady volume growth in natural gas transmission, and predictable capital projects.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>2% forever</strong> — aligning with long-term inflation targets. We use the <strong>Gordon Growth Model</strong>: Terminal Value = FCF₆ ÷ (discount rate − terminal growth rate).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>8.5%</strong>. This required rate of return balances a 4.18% 10-Year Treasury yield with WMB's defensive, regulated pipeline asset base which carries a lower beta compared to the broader market.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Add net cash, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash (-$29.3B due to massive infrastructure debt) = Equity Value. We divide by shares outstanding (1.22B) to find the per-share value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>Our valuation relies on three fundamental assumptions about WMB's future.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">4%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        WMB has a highly contracted natural gas infrastructure network. Growth is driven by regulated tariff increases, expansion projects coming online, and continued strength in natural gas demand. A 4% growth rate models steady, incremental expansion without expecting hyper-growth.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">8.5%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Given a 10Y Treasury of 4.18%, midstream energy assets traditionally demand a lower equity risk premium because cash flows are insulated by long-term take-or-pay contracts. An 8.5% discount rate provides an adequate return for this utility-like risk profile.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">2%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        In the long term, we assume pipeline assets can grow cash flow at the rate of inflation (2%). Natural gas serves as a bridge fuel in the energy transition, so while explosive growth isn't expected into perpetuity, the assets will remain critical.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FCF PROJECTIONS TABLE ═══ -->
  <h2>Projected Free Cash Flows</h2>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
          <th>FCF ($M)</th>
          <th>PV Factor</th>
          <th>Present Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Base (FY2025)</td>
          <td>${fcf2025.toLocaleString()}</td>
          <td>—</td>
          <td>—</td>
        </tr>
        {projectedFCF.map(p => (
          <tr>
            <td>Year {p.year} ({2025 + p.year})</td>
            <td>${p.fcf.toLocaleString()}</td>
            <td>{p.pvFactor.toFixed(4)}</td>
            <td>${p.pvFCF.toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
