  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what this DCF inherently misses for a midstream energy company.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Capex Drop-off:</strong> If FY2025's massive $4.89B capital expenditure is a peak, future FCF will explode upward, making our base starting point vastly understated.</li>
    <li><strong>LNG Export Boom:</strong> WMB is strategically positioned to feed US LNG export terminals. Higher than expected volumes through their pipelines would drive upside growth.</li>
    <li><strong>Asset Monetization:</strong> Selling non-core assets or spinning off parts of the business could immediately reduce debt and increase equity value.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Debt Load:</strong> With over $29 billion in debt, WMB is highly sensitive to interest rates. A prolonged high-rate environment makes refinancing expensive and eats into cash flow.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Hurdles:</strong> Building new pipelines is increasingly difficult. If WMB cannot expand its network due to environmental regulations, growth will stall.</li>
    <li><strong>Energy Transition:</strong> While natural gas is a bridge fuel, faster adoption of renewables could theoretically reduce throughput on their existing pipeline network over the long term.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of EV/EBITDA for midstream?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">EV/EBITDA is popular for pipelines because it ignores interest, taxes, and capital expenditures. However, debt servicing and maintenance capex represent real cash leaving the business. A DCF forces us to account for the heavy debt load (-$29B net cash) and actual free cash flow, providing a more grounded equity valuation.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the Intrinsic Value negative in some sensitivity scenarios?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">WMB carries a massive debt load ($29.36 billion). In scenarios with high discount rates and low growth, the present value of future cash flows isn't enough to cover this debt. The Equity Value (Enterprise Value - Debt) turns negative, theoretically rendering the equity worthless in those specific, stressed assumptions.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why did FCF drop so much in FY2025?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">WMB's capital expenditures nearly doubled from $2.57B in FY2024 to $4.89B in FY2025. While operating cash flow remained robust, these heavy investments in infrastructure severely depressed the final Free Cash Flow number for the year.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

